1
00:00:00,170 --> 00:00:03,740
In this video we are going to learn clean architecture.

2
00:00:04,040 --> 00:00:08,990
Clean architecture introduced by Robert C Martin, also known as uncle Bob.

3
00:00:09,020 --> 00:00:15,530
It is a software architecture design that aims to separate concerns and create systems that are independent

4
00:00:15,530 --> 00:00:18,260
of the frameworks, UI and databases.

5
00:00:18,650 --> 00:00:24,680
This approach leads to systems that are more maintainable, flexible and adaptable to changes.

6
00:00:25,130 --> 00:00:28,340
So let's check the key principles of the clean architecture.

7
00:00:28,370 --> 00:00:32,060
The first key principle is independence of frameworks.

8
00:00:32,060 --> 00:00:38,570
The system is not tight coupled with a specific framework, which makes it adaptable to changes in frameworks

9
00:00:38,570 --> 00:00:39,410
and tools.

10
00:00:39,860 --> 00:00:42,350
And the second principle is testable.

11
00:00:42,350 --> 00:00:48,680
The business rules can be tested without the UI, database, web server or any external element.

12
00:00:48,860 --> 00:00:53,480
And another key principle is UI agnostic UI independence.

13
00:00:53,480 --> 00:00:57,620
The UI can change easily without changing the rest of the system.

14
00:00:57,620 --> 00:01:01,310
The architecture can be unplugged from the user interface.

15
00:01:01,850 --> 00:01:07,700
And another key principle is database agnostic, which means database independence.

16
00:01:07,700 --> 00:01:10,610
The business rules are not bound to the database.

17
00:01:10,610 --> 00:01:14,510
The architecture is decoupled from the underlying data store.

18
00:01:14,810 --> 00:01:21,230
And another key principle is external system agnostic external agency independence.

19
00:01:21,230 --> 00:01:25,370
Business rules do not know anything about the outside of the world.

20
00:01:25,370 --> 00:01:31,160
The business rules of the architecture are isolated and know nothing about the outside of the world.

21
00:01:31,580 --> 00:01:34,280
And now let's check the clean architecture layers.

22
00:01:34,280 --> 00:01:36,710
The first layer is entities layer.

23
00:01:36,710 --> 00:01:38,630
Or we can say domain layer.

24
00:01:39,290 --> 00:01:43,070
Domain layer represents the business objects of the application.

25
00:01:43,070 --> 00:01:48,290
It is the core of the system and includes enterprise wide logic and business rules.

26
00:01:48,290 --> 00:01:54,380
It contains enterprise wide business rules and entities encapsulate the most general and high level

27
00:01:54,380 --> 00:01:55,010
rules.

28
00:01:55,010 --> 00:01:58,160
As an example, we can give ordering microservices.

29
00:01:58,160 --> 00:02:05,390
Entities might be ordered and order item, and the second layer is use case layer, which we can say

30
00:02:05,390 --> 00:02:06,560
application layer.

31
00:02:06,560 --> 00:02:12,530
It contains application specific business rules, and it encapsulates and implements all of the use

32
00:02:12,530 --> 00:02:13,820
cases of the system.

33
00:02:13,820 --> 00:02:20,240
As an example of the application layer use cases, we can say that create order, cancel order and update

34
00:02:20,240 --> 00:02:23,030
order status use case for ordering microservices.

35
00:02:23,570 --> 00:02:28,760
And another layer is interface adapter layers, which is the infrastructure layer.

36
00:02:29,060 --> 00:02:36,140
It basically converts data from the format most convenient for the use cases and entities to the format

37
00:02:36,140 --> 00:02:38,570
most convenient for external systems.

38
00:02:38,570 --> 00:02:43,640
As an example, we can give mapping data from database models to the domain entities.

39
00:02:43,760 --> 00:02:47,780
And the last layer we can say that frameworks and drivers.

40
00:02:47,780 --> 00:02:54,800
That means infrastructure external concerns the outermost layer consisting of the frameworks and tools

41
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:58,280
such as the database, the web framework, and so on.

42
00:02:58,640 --> 00:03:04,160
So generally includes the UI database and external interfaces and so on.

43
00:03:04,190 --> 00:03:09,050
As an example, we can say that Rest controllers and database repositories.

44
00:03:10,190 --> 00:03:16,820
So as a conclusion, we can say that clean architecture in microservices lead to system that are more

45
00:03:16,820 --> 00:03:20,420
modular, adaptable, testable and maintainable.

46
00:03:20,420 --> 00:03:27,560
We say modular because changes in one module or service don't heavily impact others, and we say adaptable

47
00:03:27,560 --> 00:03:32,270
because it is easier to update or replace technologies and databases.

48
00:03:32,270 --> 00:03:36,980
And we say testable because core logic can be tested in isolation.

49
00:03:36,980 --> 00:03:43,820
And lastly, we say maintainable because clear separation of concerns makes the system easier to understand

50
00:03:43,820 --> 00:03:44,720
and maintain.

